[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] In addition, **Narrative visualization** is a method that uses visual elements such as charts, graphs, maps and the like to convey data or information.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] This approach blends data analysis, storytelling, and visualization to present information through structured narrative flows- *using visuals not just to present statistics, but to tell a story through data*.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Its goal is to help people identify trends, patterns, and relationships in data through a compelling story-driven visual experience.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Emerging technologies like virtual, augmented and mixed reality have the potential to make information visualization more immersive, intuitive, interactive and easily manipulable and thus enhance the user's visual perception and cognition.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Effective data visualization is well-sourced, appropriately contextualized, and presented in a simple, uncluttered manner.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] The underlying data is accurate and up-to-date to ensure insights are reliable.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Graphical items are well-chosen and aesthetically appealing, with shapes, colors and other visual elements used deliberately in a meaningful and non-distracting manner.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] The visuals are accompanied by supporting texts.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Verbal and graphical components complement each other to ensure clear, quick and memorable understanding.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Effective information visualization is aware of the needs and expertise level of the target audience.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Data scientists, analysts and data mining specialists use data visualization to check data quality, find errors, unusual gaps, missing values, clean data, explore the structures and features of data, and assess outputs of data-driven models.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization can be part of *data storytelling*, where they are paired with a narrative structure, to contextualize the analyzed data and communicate insights gained from analyzing it to convince the audience into making a decision or taking action.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization is interdisciplinary, it incorporates principles found in descriptive statistics, visual communication, graphic design, cognitive science and, interactive computer graphics and human-computer interaction.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Since effective visualization requires design skills, statistical skills and computing skills, it is both an art and a science.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Visual analytics combines statistical data analysis, data and information visualization, and human analytical reasoning through interactive visual interfaces to help users reach conclusions, gain actionable insights and make informed decisions which are otherwise difficult for computers to do.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Research into how people read and misread types of visualizations helps to determine what types and features of visualizations are most understandable and effective.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Unintentionally poor or intentionally misleading and deceptive visualizations can function as powerful tools which disseminate misinformation, manipulate public perception and divert public opinion.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Thus data visualization literacy has become an important component of data and information literacy in the information age akin to the roles played by textual, mathematical and visual literacy in the past.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] The field of data and information visualization has emerged "from research in human–computer interaction, computer science, graphics, visual design, psychology, photography and business methods.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] It is increasingly applied as a critical component in scientific research, digital libraries, data mining, financial data analysis, market studies, manufacturing production control, and drug discovery".
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization presumes that "visual representations and interaction techniques take advantage of the human eye's broad bandwidth pathway into the mind to allow users to see, explore, and understand large amounts of information at once.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Data analysis is an indispensable part of all applied research and problem solving in industry.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Among these approaches, information visualization, or visual data analysis, is the most reliant on the cognitive skills of human analysts, and allows the discovery of unstructured actionable insights that are limited only by human imagination and creativity.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] The analyst does not have to learn any sophisticated methods to be able to interpret the visualizations of the data.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Information visualization is also a hypothesis generation scheme, which can be, and is typically followed by more analytical or formal analysis, such as statistical hypothesis testing.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] To communicate information clearly and efficiently, data visualization uses statistical graphics, plots, information graphics and other tools.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Numerical data may be encoded using dots, lines, or bars, to visually communicate a quantitative message.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Effective visualization helps users analyze and reason about data and evidence.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] It makes complex data more accessible, understandable, and usable, but can also be reductive.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Users may have particular analytical tasks, such as making comparisons or understanding causality, and the design principle of the graphic (i.e., showing comparisons or showing causality) follows the task.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Tables are generally used where users will look up a specific measurement, while charts of various types are used to show patterns or relationships in the data for one or more variables.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization refers to the techniques used to communicate data or information by encoding it as visual objects (e.g., points, lines, or bars) contained in graphics.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] The goal is to communicate information clearly and efficiently to users.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] It is one of the steps in data analysis or data science.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] According to Vitaly Friedman (2008) the "main goal of data visualization is to communicate information clearly and effectively through graphical means.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] It doesn't mean that data visualization needs to look boring to be functional or extremely sophisticated to look beautiful.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] To convey ideas effectively, both aesthetic form and functionality need to go hand in hand, providing insights into a rather sparse and complex data set by communicating its key aspects in a more intuitive way.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Yet designers often fail to achieve a balance between form and function, creating gorgeous data visualizations which fail to serve their main purpose — to communicate information".
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Wattenberg suggested that an ideal visualization should not only communicate clearly, but stimulate viewer engagement and attention.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization is closely related to information graphics, information visualization, scientific visualization, exploratory data analysis and statistical graphics.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] In the new millennium, data visualization has become an active area of research, teaching and development.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] (2002), it has united scientific and information visualization.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] In the commercial environment data visualization is often referred to as dashboards.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Infographics are another very common form of data visualization.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Edward Tufte has explained that users of information displays are executing particular *analytical tasks* such as making comparisons.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] The *design principle* of the information graphic should support the analytical task.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] As William Cleveland and Robert McGill show, different graphical elements accomplish this more or less effectively.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] For example, dot plots and bar charts outperform pie charts.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] In his 1983 book *The Visual Display of Quantitative Information*, Edward Tufte defines 'graphical displays' and principles for effective graphical display in the following passage: "Excellence in statistical graphics consists of complex ideas communicated with clarity, precision, and efficiency.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] For example, the Minard diagram shows the losses suffered by Napoleon's army in the 1812–1813 period.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Six variables are plotted: the size of the army, its location on a two-dimensional surface (x and y), time, the direction of movement, and temperature.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] The line width illustrates a comparison (size of the army at points in time), while the temperature axis suggests a cause of the change in army size.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] This multivariate display on a two-dimensional surface tells a story that can be grasped immediately while identifying the source data to build credibility.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Not applying these principles may result in misleading graphs, distorting the message, or supporting an erroneous conclusion.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] According to Tufte, chartjunk refers to the extraneous interior decoration of the graphic that does not enhance the message or gratuitous three-dimensional or perspective effects.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Needlessly separating the explanatory key from the image itself, requiring the eye to travel back and forth from the image to the key, is a form of "administrative debris." The ratio of "data to ink" should be maximized, erasing non-data ink where feasible.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] The Congressional Budget Office summarized several best practices for graphical displays in a June 2014 presentation.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] These included: a) Knowing your audience; b) Designing graphics that can stand alone outside the report's context; and c) Designing graphics that communicate the key messages in the report.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] For greatest efficiency and simplicity of design and user experience, this readability is enhanced through the use of bijective mapping in that design of the image elements - where the mapping of representational element to data variable is unique.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Kosara (2007) also identifies the need for a visualisation to be "recognisable as a visualisation and not appear to be something else".
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] He also states that recognisability and readability may not always be required in all types of visualisation e.g.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] "informative art" (which would still meet all three above criteria but might not look like a visualisation) or "artistic visualisation" (which similarly is still based on non-visual data to create an image, but may not be readable or recognisable).
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Ranking: Categorical subdivisions are ranked in ascending or descending order, such as a ranking of sales performance (the *measure*) by sales persons (the *category*, with each sales person a *categorical subdivision*) during a single period.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] A bar chart may be used to show the comparison across the sales persons.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Part-to-whole: Categorical subdivisions are measured as a ratio to the whole (i.e., a percentage out of 100%).
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] A pie chart or bar chart can show the comparison of ratios, such as the market share represented by competitors in a market.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Deviation: Categorical subdivisions are compared against a reference, such as a comparison of actual vs. budget expenses for several departments of a business for a given time period.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] A bar chart can show comparison of the actual versus the reference amount.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Frequency distribution: Shows the number of observations of a particular variable for given interval, such as the number of years in which the stock market return is between intervals such as 0–10%, 11–20%, etc.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] A histogram, a type of bar chart, may be used for this analysis.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] A boxplot helps visualize key statistics about the distribution, such as median, quartiles, outliers, etc.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Correlation: Comparison between observations represented by two variables (X,Y) to determine if they tend to move in the same or opposite directions.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] For example, plotting unemployment (X) and inflation (Y) for a sample of months.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] A scatter plot is typically used for this message.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Nominal comparison: Comparing categorical subdivisions in no particular order, such as the sales volume by product code.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] A bar chart may be used for this comparison.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Geographic or geospatial: Comparison of a variable across a map or layout, such as the unemployment rate by state or the number of persons on the various floors of a building.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Analysts reviewing a set of data may consider whether some or all of the messages and graphic types above are applicable to their task and audience.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] The process of trial and error to identify meaningful relationships and messages in the data is part of exploratory data analysis.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] A human can distinguish differences in line length, shape, orientation, distances, and color (hue) readily without significant processing effort; these are referred to as "pre-attentive attributes".
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] For example, it may require significant time and effort ("attentive processing") to identify the number of times the digit "5" appears in a series of numbers; but if that digit is different in size, orientation, or color, instances of the digit can be noted quickly through pre-attentive processing.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Compelling graphics take advantage of pre-attentive processing and attributes and the relative strength of these attributes.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] For example, since humans can more easily process differences in line length than surface area, it may be more effective to use a bar chart (which takes advantage of line length to show comparison) rather than pie charts (which use surface area to show comparison).
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Almost all data visualizations are created for human consumption.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Knowledge of human perception and cognition is necessary when designing intuitive visualizations.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Cognition refers to processes in human beings like perception, attention, learning, memory, thought, concept formation, reading, and problem solving.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Human visual processing is efficient in detecting changes and making comparisons between quantities, sizes, shapes and variations in lightness.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] When properties of symbolic data are mapped to visual properties, humans can browse through large amounts of data efficiently.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] It is estimated that 2/3 of the brain's neurons can be involved in visual processing.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Proper visualization provides a different approach to show potential connections, relationships, etc. which are not as obvious in non-visualized quantitative data.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Visualization can become a means of data exploration.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Studies have shown individuals used on average 19% less cognitive resources, and 4.5% better able to recall details when comparing data visualization with text.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] There is no comprehensive history of data visualization.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] There are no accounts that span the entire development of visual thinking and visual representation of data, and which collate the contributions of disparate disciplines.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Michael Friendly and Daniel Denis of York University are engaged in a project that attempts to provide a comprehensive history of visualization.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization is not a modern development.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Since prehistory, stellar data, or information such as location of stars were visualized on the walls of caves (such as those found in Lascaux Cave in Southern France) since the Pleistocene era.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Physical artefacts such as Mesopotamian clay tokens (5500 BC), Inca quipus (2600 BC) and Marshall Islands stick charts (n.d.) can also be considered as visualizing quantitative information.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] The first documented data visualization can be tracked back to 1160 B.C. with the Turin Papyrus Map which accurately illustrates the distribution of geological resources and provides information about quarrying of those resources.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Such maps can be categorized as thematic cartography, which is a type of data visualization that presents and communicates specific data and information through a geographical illustration designed to show a particular theme connected with a specific geographic area.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Earliest documented forms of data visualization were various thematic maps from different cultures and ideograms and hieroglyphs that provided and allowed interpretation of information illustrated.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] For example, Linear B tablets of Mycenae provided a visualization of information regarding Late Bronze Age era trades in the Mediterranean.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] The idea of coordinates was used by ancient Egyptian surveyors in laying out towns, earthly and heavenly positions were located by something akin to latitude and longitude at least by 200 BC, and the map projection of a spherical Earth into latitude and longitude by Claudius Ptolemy [c.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] 165] in Alexandria would serve as reference standards until the 14th century.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] The invention of paper and parchment allowed further development of visualizations.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] One graph from the 10th or possibly 11th century is an illustration of planetary movements, used in an appendix of a textbook in monastery schools.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] The graph apparently was meant to represent a plot of the inclinations of the planetary orbits as a function of the time.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] For this purpose, the zone of the zodiac was represented on a plane with a horizontal line divided into thirty parts as the time or longitudinal axis.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] The vertical axis designates the width of the zodiac.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] The horizontal scale appears to have been chosen for each planet individually for the periods cannot be reconciled.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] The accompanying text refers only to the amplitudes.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] The curves are apparently not related in time.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] By the 16th century, techniques and instruments for precise observation and measurement of physical quantities, and geographic and celestial position were well-developed (for example, a "wall quadrant" constructed by Tycho Brahe [1546–1601], covering an entire wall in his observatory).
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Particularly important were the development of triangulation and other methods to determine mapping locations accurately.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Very early, the measure of time led scholars to develop innovative way of visualizing the data (e.g.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Lorenz Codomann in 1596, Johannes Temporarius in 1596).
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Mathematicians René Descartes and Pierre de Fermat developed analytic geometry and two-dimensional coordinate system which heavily influenced the practical methods of displaying and calculating values.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Fermat and Blaise Pascal's work on statistics and probability theory laid the groundwork for what we now conceptualize as data.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] These developments helped William Playfair, who saw potential for graphical communication of quantitative data, to generate and develop graphical methods of statistics.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] In 1786, Playfair published the first presentation graphics.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] In the second half of the 20th century, Jacques Bertin used quantitative graphs to represent information "intuitively, clearly, accurately, and efficiently".
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] John Tukey and Edward Tufte pushed the bounds of data visualization; Tukey with his new statistical approach of exploratory data analysis and Tufte with his book "The Visual Display of Quantitative Information" paved the way for refining data visualization techniques for more than statisticians.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] With the progression of technology came the progression of data visualization; starting with hand-drawn visualizations and evolving into more technical applications – including interactive designs leading to software visualization.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] The modern study of visualization started with computer graphics, which "has from its beginning been used to study scientific problems.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] However, in its early days the lack of graphics power often limited its usefulness.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] The recent emphasis on visualization started in 1987 with the special issue of Computer Graphics on Visualization in *Scientific Computing*.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Since then there have been several conferences and workshops, co-sponsored by the IEEE Computer Society and ACM SIGGRAPH".
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] They have been devoted to the general topics of data visualization, information visualization and scientific visualization, and more specific areas such as volume visualization.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Programs like SAS, SOFA, R, Minitab, Cornerstone and more allow for data visualization in the field of statistics.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Other data visualization applications, more focused and unique to individuals, programming languages such as D3, Python (through matplotlib, seaborn) and JavaScript and Java(through JavaFX) help to make the visualization of quantitative data a possibility.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Private schools have also developed programs to meet the demand for learning data visualization and associated programming libraries, including free programs like The Data Incubator or paid programs like General Assembly.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Beginning with the symposium "Data to Discovery" in 2013, ArtCenter College of Design, Caltech and JPL in Pasadena have run an annual program on interactive data visualization.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] The program asks: How can interactive data visualization help scientists and engineers explore their data more effectively?
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] How can computing, design, and design thinking help maximize research results?
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] What methodologies are most effective for leveraging knowledge from these fields?
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] In recent years, with the increasing popularity of games, data and information visualization has been gradually applied in the gaming industry through the use of analytical tools to assess player statistics and game performance, which are visualized in the form of health points, maps, and diagrams.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] The data is then collected and stored by developers.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] The implementation of these tools in gaming assists developers in improving user experience and in the development and updating of newer games.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization involves specific terminology, some of which is derived from statistics.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] The distinction between quantitative and categorical variables is important because the two types require different methods of visualization.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Two primary types of information displays are tables and graphs.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Eppler and Lengler have developed the "Periodic Table of Visualization Methods," an interactive chart displaying various data visualization methods.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] It includes six types of data visualization methods: data, information, concept, strategy, metaphor and compound.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Interactive data visualization has been a pursuit of statisticians since the late 1960s.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Examples of the developments can be found on the American Statistical Association video lending library.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] There are different approaches on the scope of data visualization.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] One common focus is on information presentation, such as Friedman (2008).
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Friendly (2008) presumes two main parts of data visualization: statistical graphics, and thematic cartography.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] All these subjects are closely related to graphic design and information representation.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Within The Harvard Business Review, Scott Berinato developed a framework to approach data visualisation.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] To start thinking visually, users must consider two questions; 1) What you have and 2) what you're doing.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] The first step is identifying what data you want visualised.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] It is data-driven like profit over the past ten years or a conceptual idea like how a specific organisation is structured.
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Once this question is answered one can then focus on whether they are trying to communicate information (declarative visualisation) or trying to figure something out (exploratory visualisation).
[src:weights-and-biases/data-visualization-p01] Scott Berinato combines these questions to give four types of visual communication that each have their own goals.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] An **experiment** is a procedure carried out to support or refute a hypothesis, or determine the efficacy or likelihood of something previously untried.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Experiments provide insight into cause-and-effect by demonstrating what outcome occurs when a particular factor is manipulated.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Experiments vary greatly in goal and scale but always rely on repeatable procedure and logical analysis of the results.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] There also exist natural experimental studies.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] A child may carry out basic experiments to understand how things fall to the ground, while teams of scientists may take years of systematic investigation to advance their understanding of a phenomenon.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Experiments and other types of hands-on activities are very important to student learning in the science classroom.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Experiments can raise test scores and help a student become more engaged and interested in the material they are learning, especially when used over time.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Experiments can vary from personal and informal natural comparisons (e.g. tasting a range of chocolates to find a favorite), to highly controlled (e.g. tests requiring complex apparatus overseen by many scientists that hope to discover information about subatomic particles).
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Uses of experiments vary considerably between the natural and human sciences.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Experiments typically include controls, which are designed to minimize the effects of variables other than the single independent variable.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] This increases the reliability of the results, often through a comparison between control measurements and the other measurements.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Scientific controls are a part of the scientific method.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Ideally, all variables in an experiment are controlled (accounted for by the control measurements) and none are uncontrolled.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] In such an experiment, if all controls work as expected, it is possible to conclude that the experiment works as intended, and that results are due to the effect of the tested variables.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] In the scientific method, an experiment is an empirical procedure that arbitrates competing models or hypotheses.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Researchers also use experimentation to test existing theories or new hypotheses to support or disprove them.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] An experiment usually tests a hypothesis, which is an expectation about how a particular process or phenomenon works.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] However, an experiment may also aim to answer a "what-if" question, without a specific expectation about what the experiment reveals, or to confirm prior results.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] If an experiment is carefully conducted, the results usually either support or disprove the hypothesis.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] According to some philosophies of science, an experiment can never "prove" a hypothesis, it can only add support.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] On the other hand, an experiment that provides a counterexample can disprove a theory or hypothesis, but a theory can always be salvaged by appropriate ad hoc modifications at the expense of simplicity.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] An experiment must also control the possible confounding factors—any factors that would mar the accuracy or repeatability of the experiment or the ability to interpret the results.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Confounding is commonly eliminated through scientific controls and/or, in randomized experiments, through random assignment.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] In engineering and the physical sciences, experiments are a primary component of the scientific method.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] They are used to test theories and hypotheses about how physical processes work under particular conditions (e.g., whether a particular engineering process can produce a desired chemical compound).
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Typically, experiments in these fields focus on replication of identical procedures in hopes of producing identical results in each replication.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] In medicine and the social sciences, the prevalence of experimental research varies widely across disciplines.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] When used, however, experiments typically follow the form of the clinical trial, where experimental units (usually individual human beings) are randomly assigned to a treatment or control condition where one or more outcomes are assessed.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] In contrast to norms in the physical sciences, the focus is typically on the average treatment effect (the difference in outcomes between the treatment and control groups) or another test statistic produced by the experiment.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] A single study typically does not involve replications of the experiment, but separate studies may be aggregated through systematic review and meta-analysis.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] There are various differences in experimental practice in each of the branches of science.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Several scholars have noted that the account in *Daniel* 1:12–16 contains one of the earliest descriptions of a controlled comparative test in ancient literature.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] In the narrative, Daniel and his companions request a ten-day trial in which they consume only vegetables and water, while other youths continue on the king’s diet.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] The results of the two regimens are compared, and the steward is instructed to act based on the observable outcome.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Historians of science have occasionally referenced this passage as an early literary example of empirical reasoning.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Lindberg notes that the Hebrew Bible contains "procedures that resemble empirical testing," and includes Daniel 1 among examples where a trial is deliberately arranged to evaluate competing conditions.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] VanderKam likewise describes the episode as presenting "a rudimentary experimental design" contrasting two diets under controlled circumstances.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] While this view is not universal, some commentators have referred to the episode as one of the earliest recorded experimental tests.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] One of the first methodical approaches to experiments in the modern sense is visible in the works of the Arab mathematician and scholar Ibn al-Haytham.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] He conducted his experiments in the field of optics—going back to optical and mathematical problems in the works of Ptolemy—by controlling his experiments due to factors such as self-criticality, reliance on visible results of the experiments as well as a criticality in terms of earlier results.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] He was one of the first scholars to use an inductive-experimental method for achieving results.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] According to his explanation, a strictly controlled test execution with a sensibility for the subjectivity and susceptibility of outcomes due to the nature of man is necessary.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Thus, a comparison of earlier results with the experimental results is necessary for an objective experiment—the visible results being more important.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] In the end, this may mean that an experimental researcher must find enough courage to discard traditional opinions or results, especially if these results are not experimental but results from a logical/ mental derivation.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] In this process of critical consideration, the man himself should not forget that he tends to subjective opinions—through "prejudices" and "leniency"—and thus has to be critical about his own way of building hypotheses.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Francis Bacon (1561–1626), an English philosopher and scientist active in the 17th century, became an influential supporter of experimental science in the English renaissance.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Notably, he first ordered the scientific method as we understand it today.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] In the centuries that followed, people who applied the scientific method in different areas made important advances and discoveries.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] For example, Galileo Galilei (1564–1642) accurately measured time and experimented to make accurate measurements and conclusions about the speed of a falling body.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Antoine Lavoisier (1743–1794), a French chemist, used experiment to describe new areas, such as combustion and biochemistry and to develop the theory of conservation of mass (matter).
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Louis Pasteur (1822–1895) used the scientific method to disprove the prevailing theory of spontaneous generation and to develop the germ theory of disease.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Because of the importance of controlling potentially confounding variables, the use of well-designed laboratory experiments is preferred when possible.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Experiments might be categorized according to a number of dimensions, depending upon professional norms and standards in different fields of study.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] In some disciplines (e.g., psychology or political science), a 'true experiment' is a method of social research in which there are two kinds of variables.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] The independent variable is manipulated by the experimenter, and the dependent variable is measured.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] The signifying characteristic of a true experiment is that it randomly allocates the subjects to neutralize experimenter bias, and ensures, over a large number of iterations of the experiment, that it controls for all confounding factors.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Depending on the discipline, experiments can be conducted to accomplish different but not mutually exclusive goals: test theories, search for and document phenomena, develop theories, or advise policymakers.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] These goals also relate differently to validity concerns.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] A controlled experiment often compares the results obtained from experimental samples against *control* samples, which are practically identical to the experimental sample except for the one aspect whose effect is being tested (the independent variable).
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] The sample or group receiving the drug would be the experimental group (treatment group); and the one receiving the placebo or regular treatment would be the control one.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] In many laboratory experiments it is good practice to have several replicate samples for the test being performed and have both a positive control and a negative control.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Most often, tests are done in duplicate or triplicate.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] A positive control is a procedure similar to the actual experimental test but is known from previous experience to give a positive result.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] A negative control is known to give a negative result.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] The positive control confirms that the basic conditions of the experiment were able to produce a positive result, even if none of the actual experimental samples produce a positive result.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] The negative control demonstrates the base-line result obtained when a test does not produce a measurable positive result.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Most often the value of the negative control is treated as a "background" value to subtract from the test sample results.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Sometimes the positive control takes the quadrant of a standard curve.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] An example that is often used in teaching laboratories is a controlled protein assay.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Students might be given a fluid sample containing an unknown (to the student) amount of protein.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] It is their job to correctly perform a controlled experiment in which they determine the concentration of protein in the fluid sample (usually called the "unknown sample").
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] The teaching lab would be equipped with a protein standard solution with a known protein concentration.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Students could make several positive control samples containing various dilutions of the protein standard.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Negative control samples would contain all of the reagents for the protein assay but no protein.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] In this example, all samples are performed in duplicate.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] The assay is a colorimetric assay in which a spectrophotometer can measure the amount of protein in samples by detecting a colored complex formed by the interaction of protein molecules and molecules of an added dye.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] In the illustration, the results for the diluted test samples can be compared to the results of the standard curve (the blue line in the illustration) to estimate the amount of protein in the unknown sample.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Controlled experiments can be performed when it is difficult to exactly control all the conditions in an experiment.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] In this case, the experiment begins by creating two or more sample groups that are probabilistically equivalent, which means that measurements of traits should be similar among the groups and that the groups should respond in the same manner if given the same treatment.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] This equivalency is determined by statistical methods that take into account the amount of variation between individuals and the number of individuals in each group.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] In fields such as microbiology and chemistry, where there is very little variation between individuals and the group size is easily in the millions, these statistical methods are often bypassed and simply splitting a solution into equal parts is assumed to produce identical sample groups.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Once equivalent groups have been formed, the experimenter tries to treat them identically except for the one *variable* that he or she wishes to isolate.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Human experimentation requires special safeguards against outside variables such as the *placebo effect*.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Such experiments are generally *double blind*, meaning that neither the volunteer nor the researcher knows which individuals are in the control group or the experimental group until after all of the data have been collected.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] This ensures that any effects on the volunteer are due to the treatment itself and are not a response to the knowledge that he is being treated.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] In human experiments, researchers may give a subject (person) a stimulus that the subject responds to.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] The goal of the experiment is to measure the response to the stimulus by a test method.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] In the design of experiments, two or more "treatments" are applied to estimate the difference between the mean responses for the treatments.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] For example, an experiment on baking bread could estimate the difference in the responses associated with quantitative variables, such as the ratio of water to flour, and with qualitative variables, such as strains of yeast.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Experimentation is the step in the scientific method that helps people decide between two or more competing explanations—or hypotheses.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] These hypotheses suggest reasons to explain a phenomenon or predict the results of an action.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] An example might be the hypothesis that "if I release this ball, it will fall to the floor": this suggestion can then be tested by carrying out the experiment of letting go of the ball, and observing the results.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Formally, a hypothesis is compared against its opposite or null hypothesis ("if I release this ball, it will not fall to the floor").
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] The null hypothesis is that there is no explanation or predictive power of the phenomenon through the reasoning that is being investigated.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Once hypotheses are defined, an experiment can be carried out and the results analysed to confirm, refute, or define the accuracy of the hypotheses.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Experiments can be also designed to estimate spillover effects onto nearby untreated units.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] The term "experiment" usually implies a controlled experiment, but sometimes controlled experiments are prohibitively difficult, impossible, unethical or illegal.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] In this case researchers resort to natural experiments or quasi-experiments.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Natural experiments rely solely on observations of the variables of the system under study, rather than manipulation of just one or a few variables as occurs in controlled experiments.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] To the degree possible, they attempt to collect data for the system in such a way that contribution from all variables can be determined, and where the effects of variation in certain variables remain approximately constant so that the effects of other variables can be discerned.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] The degree to which this is possible depends on the observed correlation between explanatory variables in the observed data.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] When these variables are *not* well correlated, natural experiments can approach the power of controlled experiments.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Usually, however, there is some correlation between these variables, which reduces the reliability of natural experiments relative to what could be concluded if a controlled experiment were performed.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Also, because natural experiments usually take place in uncontrolled environments, variables from undetected sources are neither measured nor held constant, and these may produce illusory correlations in variables under study.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Much research in several science disciplines, including economics, human geography, archaeology, sociology, cultural anthropology, geology, paleontology, ecology, meteorology, and astronomy, relies on quasi-experiments.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] For example, in astronomy it is clearly impossible, when testing the hypothesis "Stars are collapsed clouds of hydrogen", to start out with a giant cloud of hydrogen, and then perform the experiment of waiting a few billion years for it to form a star.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] However, by observing various clouds of hydrogen in various states of collapse, and other implications of the hypothesis (for example, the presence of various spectral emissions from the light of stars), we can collect data we require to support the hypothesis.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] An early example of this type of experiment was the first verification in the 17th century that light does not travel from place to place instantaneously, but instead has a measurable speed.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Field experiments are so named to distinguish them from laboratory experiments, which enforce scientific control by testing a hypothesis in the artificial and highly controlled setting of a laboratory.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Often used in the social sciences, and especially in economic analyses of education and health interventions, field experiments have the advantage that outcomes are observed in a natural setting rather than in a contrived laboratory environment.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] For this reason, field experiments are sometimes seen as having higher external validity than laboratory experiments.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] However, like natural experiments, field experiments suffer from the possibility of contamination: experimental conditions can be controlled with more precision and certainty in the lab.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Yet some phenomena (e.g., voter turnout in an election) cannot be easily studied in a laboratory.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] An observational study is used when it is impractical, unethical, cost-prohibitive (or otherwise inefficient) to fit a physical or social system into a laboratory setting, to completely control confounding factors, or to apply random assignment.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] It can also be used when confounding factors are either limited or known well enough to analyze the data in light of them (though this may be rare when social phenomena are under examination).
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] For an observational science to be valid, the experimenter must know and account for confounding factors.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] In these situations, observational studies have value because they often suggest hypotheses that can be tested with randomized experiments or by collecting fresh data.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Fundamentally, however, observational studies are not experiments.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] By definition, observational studies lack the manipulation required for Baconian experiments.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] In addition, observational studies (e.g., in biological or social systems) often involve variables that are difficult to quantify or control.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Observational studies are limited because they lack the statistical properties of randomized experiments.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] In a randomized experiment, the method of randomization specified in the experimental protocol guides the statistical analysis, which is usually specified also by the experimental protocol.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Without a statistical model that reflects an objective randomization, the statistical analysis relies on a subjective model.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Inferences from subjective models are unreliable in theory and practice.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] In fact, there are several cases where carefully conducted observational studies consistently give wrong results, that is, where the results of the observational studies are inconsistent and also differ from the results of experiments.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] For example, epidemiological studies of colon cancer consistently show beneficial correlations with broccoli consumption, while experiments find no benefit.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] In contrast, randomization implies that for each covariate, the mean for each group is expected to be the same.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] For any randomized trial, some variation from the mean is expected, of course, but the randomization ensures that the experimental groups have mean values that are close, due to the central limit theorem and Markov's inequality.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] With inadequate randomization or low sample size, the systematic variation in covariates between the treatment groups (or exposure groups) makes it difficult to separate the effect of the treatment (exposure) from the effects of the other covariates, most of which have not been measured.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] The mathematical models used to analyze such data must consider each differing covariate (if measured), and results are not meaningful if a covariate is neither randomized nor included in the model.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] To avoid conditions that render an experiment far less useful, physicians conducting medical trials—say for U.S.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Food and Drug Administration approval—quantify and randomize the covariates that can be identified.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Researchers attempt to reduce the biases of observational studies with matching methods such as propensity score matching, which require large populations of subjects and extensive information on covariates.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] However, propensity score matching is no longer recommended as a technique because it can increase, rather than decrease, bias.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Outcomes are also quantified when possible (bone density, the amount of some cell or substance in the blood, physical strength or endurance, etc.) and not based on a subject's or a professional observer's opinion.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] In this way, the design of an observational study can render the results more objective and therefore, more convincing.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] For example, in psychology or health care, it is unethical to provide a substandard treatment to patients.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Therefore, ethical review boards are supposed to stop clinical trials and other experiments unless a new treatment is believed to offer benefits as good as current best practice.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] It is also generally unethical (and often illegal) to conduct randomized experiments on the effects of substandard or harmful treatments, such as the effects of ingesting arsenic on human health.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] To understand the effects of such exposures, scientists sometimes use observational studies to understand the effects of those factors.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] Even when experimental research does not directly involve human subjects, it may still present ethical concerns.
[src:weights-and-biases/experiment] For example, the nuclear bomb experiments conducted by the Manhattan Project implied the use of nuclear reactions to harm human beings even though the experiments did not directly involve any human subjects.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] In machine learning, **hyperparameter optimization** or tuning is the problem of choosing a set of optimal hyperparameters for a learning algorithm.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] A hyperparameter is a parameter whose value is used to control the learning process, which must be configured before the process starts.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] Hyperparameter optimization determines the set of hyperparameters that yields an optimal model which minimizes a predefined loss function on a given data set.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] The objective function takes a set of hyperparameters and returns the associated loss.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] Cross-validation is often used to estimate this generalization performance, and therefore choose the set of values for hyperparameters that maximize it.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] The traditional method for hyperparameter optimization has been *grid search*, or a *parameter sweep*, which is simply an exhaustive searching through a manually specified subset of the hyperparameter space of a learning algorithm.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] A grid search algorithm must be guided by some performance metric, typically measured by cross-validation on the training set or evaluation on a hold-out validation set.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] Since the parameter space of a machine learner may include real-valued or unbounded value spaces for certain parameters, manually set bounds and discretization may be necessary before applying grid search.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] For example, a typical soft-margin SVM classifier equipped with an RBF kernel has at least two hyperparameters that need to be tuned for good performance on unseen data: a regularization constant *C* and a kernel hyperparameter γ.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] Grid search then trains an SVM with each pair (*C*, γ) in the Cartesian product of these two sets and evaluates their performance on a held-out validation set (or by internal cross-validation on the training set, in which case multiple SVMs are trained per pair).
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] Finally, the grid search algorithm outputs the settings that achieved the highest score in the validation procedure.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] Grid search suffers from the curse of dimensionality, but is often embarrassingly parallel because the hyperparameter settings it evaluates are typically independent of each other.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] Random Search replaces the exhaustive enumeration of all combinations by selecting them randomly.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] This can be simply applied to the discrete setting described above, but also generalizes to continuous and mixed spaces.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] A benefit over grid search is that random search can explore many more values than grid search could for continuous hyperparameters.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] It can outperform Grid search, especially when only a small number of hyperparameters affects the final performance of the machine learning algorithm.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] In this case, the optimization problem is said to have a low intrinsic dimensionality.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] Random Search is also embarrassingly parallel, and additionally allows the inclusion of prior knowledge by specifying the distribution from which to sample.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] Despite its simplicity, random search remains one of the important base-lines against which to compare the performance of new hyperparameter optimization methods.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] Bayesian optimization is a global optimization method for noisy black-box functions.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] Applied to hyperparameter optimization, Bayesian optimization builds a probabilistic model of the function mapping from hyperparameter values to the objective evaluated on a validation set.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] By iteratively evaluating a promising hyperparameter configuration based on the current model, and then updating it, Bayesian optimization aims to gather observations revealing as much information as possible about this function and, in particular, the location of the optimum.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] It tries to balance exploration (hyperparameters for which the outcome is most uncertain) and exploitation (hyperparameters expected close to the optimum).
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] In practice, Bayesian optimization has been shown to obtain better results in fewer evaluations compared to grid search and random search, due to the ability to reason about the quality of experiments before they are run.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] For specific learning algorithms, it is possible to compute the gradient with respect to hyperparameters and then optimize the hyperparameters using gradient descent.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] The first usage of these techniques was focused on neural networks.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] Since then, these methods have been extended to other models such as support vector machines or logistic regression.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] A different approach in order to obtain a gradient with respect to hyperparameters consists in differentiating the steps of an iterative optimization algorithm using automatic differentiation.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] A more recent work along this direction uses the implicit function theorem to calculate hypergradients and proposes a stable approximation of the inverse Hessian.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] The method scales to millions of hyperparameters and requires constant memory.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] In a different approach, a hypernetwork is trained to approximate the best response function.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] One of the advantages of this method is that it can handle discrete hyperparameters as well.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] Self-tuning networks offer a memory efficient version of this approach by choosing a compact representation for the hypernetwork.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] Apart from hypernetwork approaches, gradient-based methods can be used to optimize discrete hyperparameters also by adopting a continuous relaxation of the parameters.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] Such methods have been extensively used for the optimization of architecture hyperparameters in neural architecture search.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] Evolutionary optimization is a methodology for the global optimization of noisy black-box functions.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] In hyperparameter optimization, evolutionary optimization uses evolutionary algorithms to search the space of hyperparameters for a given algorithm.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] Repeat steps 2-4 until satisfactory algorithm performance is reached or is no longer improving.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] Evolutionary optimization has been used in hyperparameter optimization for statistical machine learning algorithms, automated machine learning, typical neural network and deep neural network architecture search, as well as training of the weights in deep neural networks.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] Population Based Training (PBT) learns both hyperparameter values and network weights.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] Multiple learning processes operate independently, using different hyperparameters.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] As with evolutionary methods, poorly performing models are iteratively replaced with models that adopt modified hyperparameter values and weights based on the better performers.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] This replacement model warm starting is the primary differentiator between PBT and other evolutionary methods.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] PBT thus allows the hyperparameters to evolve and eliminates the need for manual hypertuning.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] The process makes no assumptions regarding model architecture, loss functions or training procedures.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] PBT and its variants are adaptive methods: they update hyperparameters during the training of the models.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] On the contrary, non-adaptive methods have the sub-optimal strategy to assign a constant set of hyperparameters for the whole training.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] A class of early stopping-based hyperparameter optimization algorithms is purpose-built for large search spaces of continuous and discrete hyperparameters, particularly when the computational cost to evaluate the performance of a set of hyperparameters is high.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] Irace implements the iterated racing algorithm, that focuses the search around the most promising configurations, using statistical tests to discard the ones that perform poorly.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] Another early stopping hyperparameter optimization algorithm is successive halving (SHA), which begins as a random search but periodically prunes low-performing models, thereby focusing computational resources on more promising models.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] Asynchronous successive halving (ASHA) further improves upon SHA's resource utilization profile by removing the need to synchronously evaluate and prune low-performing models.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] Hyperband is a higher level early stopping-based algorithm that invokes SHA or ASHA multiple times with varying levels of pruning aggressiveness, in order to be more widely applicable and with fewer required inputs.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] RBF and spectral approaches have also been developed.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] When hyperparameter optimization is done, the set of hyperparameters are often fitted on a training set and selected based on the generalization performance, or score, of a validation set.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] However, this procedure is at risk of overfitting the hyperparameters to the validation set.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] Therefore, the generalization performance score of the validation set (which can be several sets in the case of a cross-validation procedure) cannot be used to simultaneously estimate the generalization performance of the final model.
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] In order to do so, the generalization performance has to be evaluated on a set independent (which has no intersection) of the set (or sets) used for the optimization of the hyperparameters, otherwise the performance might give a value which is too optimistic (too large).
[src:weights-and-biases/hyperparameter-optimization] This can be done on a second test set, or through an outer cross-validation procedure called nested cross-validation, which allows an unbiased estimation of the generalization performance of the model, taking into account the bias due to the hyperparameter optimization.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Statistics and mathematical optimisation methods compose the foundations of machine learning.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Data mining is a related field of study, focusing on exploratory data analysis (EDA) through unsupervised learning.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] From a theoretical viewpoint, probably approximately correct learning provides a mathematical and statistical framework for describing machine learning.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Most traditional machine learning and deep learning algorithms can be described as empirical risk minimisation under this framework.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] The term *machine learning* was coined in 1959 by Arthur Samuel, an IBM employee and pioneer in the field of computer gaming and artificial intelligence.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] The synonym *self-teaching computers* was also used during this time period.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] The earliest machine learning program was introduced in the 1950s, when Samuel invented a computer program that calculated the chance of winning in checkers for each side, but the history of machine learning is rooted in decades of efforts to study human cognitive processes.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] In 1949, Canadian psychologist Donald Hebb published the book *The Organization of Behavior*, in which he introduced a theoretical neural structure formed by certain interactions among nerve cells.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] The Hebbian theory of neuron interaction set the groundwork for how many machine learning algorithms work, with connected artificial neurons changing the strength of their connections based on data.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Other researchers who have studied human cognitive systems contributed to the modern machine learning technologies as well, including Walter Pitts and Warren McCulloch, who proposed the first mathematical model of neural networks including algorithms that mirror human thought processes.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] By the early 1960s, an experimental "learning machine" with punched tape memory, called Cybertron, had been developed by Raytheon Company to analyse sonar signals, electrocardiograms, and speech patterns using rudimentary reinforcement learning.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] It was repetitively "trained" by a human operator/teacher to recognise patterns and equipped with a "goof" button to cause it to reevaluate incorrect decisions.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] A representative book on research into machine learning during the 1960s was Nils Nilsson's book "Learning Machines", dealing mostly with machine learning for pattern classification.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Interest related to pattern recognition continued into the 1970s, as described by Duda and Hart in 1973.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] In 1981, a report was given on using teaching strategies so that an artificial neural network learns to recognise 40 characters (26 letters, 10 digits, and 4 special symbols) from a computer terminal.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] This follows Alan Turing's proposal in his paper "Computing Machinery and Intelligence", in which the question, "Can machines think?", is replaced by asking whether machines can convincingly imitate a human in its responses to human-posed questions.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] In 2014 Ian Goodfellow and others introduced generative adversarial networks (GANs) which could produce realistic synthetic data.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] By 2016 AlphaGo had won against top human players in Go using reinforcement learning techniques.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] As a scientific endeavour, machine learning grew out of the quest for artificial intelligence (AI).
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] In the early days of AI as an academic discipline, some researchers were interested in having machines learn from data.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] They attempted to approach the problem with various symbolic methods, as well as what were then termed "neural networks"; these were mostly perceptrons and other models that were later found to be reinventions of the generalised linear models of statistics.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Probabilistic reasoning was also employed, especially in automated medical diagnosis.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] However, an increasing emphasis on the logical, knowledge-based approach caused a rift between AI and machine learning.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Probabilistic systems were plagued by theoretical and practical problems of data acquisition and representation.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] By 1980, expert systems had come to dominate AI, and statistics was out of favour.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Work on symbolic/knowledge-based learning continued within AI, leading to inductive logic programming (ILP), but the more statistical line of research was now outside the field of AI proper, in pattern recognition and information retrieval.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Neural network research was abandoned by AI and computer science around the same time.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] This subfield, termed "connectionism", was continued by researchers from other disciplines, including John Hopfield, David Rumelhart, and Geoffrey Hinton.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Their main success came in the mid-1980s with the reinvention of backpropagation.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Machine learning (ML), reorganised and recognised as its own field, started to flourish in the 1990s.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] The field changed its goal from achieving artificial intelligence to tackling solvable problems of a practical nature.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] It shifted focus away from the symbolic approaches it had inherited from AI, and toward methods and models borrowed from statistics, fuzzy logic, and probability theory.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] There is a close connection between machine learning and compression.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] A system that predicts the posterior probabilities of a sequence given its entire history can be used for optimal data compression (by using arithmetic coding on the output distribution).
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Conversely, an optimal compressor can be used for prediction (by finding the symbol that compresses best, given the previous history).
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] This equivalence has been used as a justification for using data compression as a benchmark for "general intelligence".
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] An alternative view can show compression algorithms implicitly map strings into implicit feature space vectors, and compression-based similarity measures compute similarity within these feature spaces.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] For each compressor C(.) we define an associated vector space ℵ, such that C(.) maps an input string x, corresponding to the vector norm ||~x||.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] An exhaustive examination of the feature spaces underlying all compression algorithms is precluded by space; instead, feature vectors chooses to examine three representative lossless compression methods, LZW, LZ77, and PPM.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] According to AIXI theory, a connection more directly explained in Hutter Prize, the best possible compression of x is the smallest possible software that generates x.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] For example, in that model, a zip file's compressed size includes both the zip file and the unzipping software, since you can not unzip it without both, but there may be an even smaller combined form.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Examples of AI-powered audio/video compression software include NVIDIA Maxine, AIVC.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Examples of software that can perform AI-powered image compression include OpenCV, TensorFlow, MATLAB's Image Processing Toolbox (IPT) and High-Fidelity Generative Image Compression.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] In unsupervised machine learning, k-means clustering can be utilized to compress data by grouping similar data points into clusters.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] This technique simplifies handling extensive datasets that lack predefined labels and finds widespread use in fields such as image compression.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Data compression aims to reduce the size of data files, enhancing storage efficiency and speeding up data transmission.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] K-means clustering, an unsupervised machine learning algorithm, is employed to partition a dataset into a specified number of clusters, k, each represented by the centroid of its points.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] This process condenses extensive datasets into a more compact set of representative points.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Particularly beneficial in image and signal processing, k-means clustering aids in data reduction by replacing groups of data points with their centroids, thereby preserving the core information of the original data while significantly decreasing the required storage space.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Large language models (LLMs) are also efficient lossless data compressors on some data sets, as demonstrated by DeepMind's research with the Chinchilla 70B model.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Developed by DeepMind, Chinchilla 70B effectively compressed data, outperforming conventional methods such as Portable Network Graphics (PNG) for images and Free Lossless Audio Codec (FLAC) for audio.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] It achieved compression of image and audio data to 43.4% and 16.4% of their original sizes, respectively.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] There is, however, some reason to be concerned that the data set used for testing overlaps the LLM training data set, making it possible that the Chinchilla 70B model is only an efficient compression tool on data it has already been trained on.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Data mining uses many machine learning methods, but with different goals; on the other hand, machine learning also employs data mining methods as "unsupervised learning" or as a preprocessing step to improve learner accuracy.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Evaluated with respect to known knowledge, an uninformed (unsupervised) method will easily be outperformed by other supervised methods, while in a typical KDD task, supervised methods cannot be used due to the unavailability of training data.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Machine learning also has intimate ties to optimization: Many learning problems are formulated as minimisation of some loss function on a training set of examples.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Loss functions express the discrepancy between the predictions of the model being trained and the actual problem instances (for example, in classification, one wants to assign a label to instances, and models are trained to correctly predict the preassigned labels of a set of examples).
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Characterizing the generalisation of various learning algorithms is an active topic of current research, especially for deep learning algorithms.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Machine learning and statistics are closely related fields in terms of methods, but distinct in their principal goal: statistics draws population inferences from a sample, while machine learning finds generalisable predictive patterns.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Conventional statistical analyses require the a priori selection of a model most suitable for the study data set.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] In addition, only significant or theoretically relevant variables based on previous experience are included for analysis.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] In contrast, machine learning is not built on a pre-structured model; rather, the data shape the model by detecting underlying patterns.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] The more variables (input) used to train the model, the more accurate the ultimate model will be.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Leo Breiman distinguished two statistical modelling paradigms: the data model and the algorithmic model, wherein "algorithmic model" means more or less the machine learning algorithms like Random forest.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Some statisticians have adopted methods from machine learning, producing the field of *statistical learning*.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Analytical and computational techniques derived from deep-rooted physics of disordered systems can be extended to large-scale problems, including machine learning, e.g., to analyse the weight space of deep neural networks.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Statistical physics is thus finding applications in the area of medical diagnostics.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] A core objective of a learner is to generalise from its experience.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Generalisation in this context is the ability of a learning machine to perform accurately on new, unseen examples/tasks after having experienced a learning data set.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] The training examples come from some generally unknown probability distribution (considered representative of the space of occurrences) and the learner has to build a general model about this space that enables it to produce sufficiently accurate predictions in new cases.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] The computational analysis of machine learning algorithms and their performance is a branch of theoretical computer science known as computational learning theory.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] One major framework is the probably approximately correct learning model.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Because training sets are finite and the future is uncertain, learning theory usually does not yield guarantees of the performance of algorithms.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Instead, probabilistic bounds on the performance are quite common.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] The bias–variance decomposition is one way to quantify generalisation error.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] For the best performance in the context of generalisation, the complexity of the hypothesis should match the complexity of the function underlying the data.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] If the hypothesis is less complex than the function, then the model has underfitted the data.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] If the complexity of the model is increased in response, then the training error decreases.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] But if the hypothesis is too complex, then the model is subject to overfitting and generalisation will be poorer.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] In addition to performance bounds, learning theorists study the time complexity and feasibility of learning.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] In computational learning theory, a computation is considered feasible if it can be done in polynomial time.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] There are two kinds of time complexity results: Positive results show that a certain class of functions can be learned in polynomial time.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Negative results show that certain classes cannot be learned in polynomial time.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Although each algorithm has advantages and limitations, no single algorithm works for all problems.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Supervised learning algorithms build a mathematical model of a set of data that contains both the inputs and the desired outputs.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] The data, known as training data, consists of a set of training examples.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Each training example has one or more inputs and the desired output, also known as a supervisory signal.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] In the mathematical model, each training example is represented by an array or vector, sometimes called a feature vector, and the training data is represented by a matrix.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Through iterative optimisation of an objective function, supervised learning algorithms learn a function that can be used to predict the output associated with new inputs.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] An optimal function allows the algorithm to correctly determine the output for inputs that were not a part of the training data.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] An algorithm that improves the accuracy of its outputs or predictions over time is said to have learned to perform that task.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Types of supervised-learning algorithms include active learning, classification and regression.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Classification algorithms are used when the outputs are restricted to a limited set of values, while regression algorithms are used when the outputs can take any numerical value within a range.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] For example, in a classification algorithm that filters emails, the input is an incoming email, and the output is the folder in which to file the email.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] In contrast, regression is used for tasks such as predicting a person's height based on factors like age and genetics or forecasting future temperatures based on historical data.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Similarity learning is an area of supervised machine learning closely related to regression and classification, but the goal is to learn from examples using a similarity function that measures how similar or related two objects are.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] It has applications in ranking, recommendation systems, visual identity tracking, face verification, and speaker verification.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Unsupervised learning algorithms find structures in data that has not been labelled, classified or categorised.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Instead of responding to feedback, unsupervised learning algorithms identify commonalities in the data and react based on the presence or absence of such commonalities in each new piece of data.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Central applications of unsupervised machine learning include clustering, dimensionality reduction, and density estimation.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Cluster analysis is the assignment of a set of observations into subsets (called *clusters*) so that observations within the same cluster are similar according to one or more predesignated criteria, while observations drawn from different clusters are dissimilar.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Different clustering techniques make different assumptions on the structure of the data, often defined by some *similarity metric* and evaluated, for example, by *internal compactness*, or the similarity between members of the same cluster, and *separation*, the difference between clusters.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Other methods are based on *estimated density* and *graph connectivity*.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] A special type of unsupervised learning called self-supervised learning involves training a model by generating the supervisory signal from the data itself.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Dimensionality reduction is a process of reducing the number of random variables under consideration by obtaining a set of principal variables.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] In other words, it is a process of reducing the dimension of the feature set, also called the "number of features".
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Most of the dimensionality reduction techniques can be considered as either feature elimination or extraction.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] One of the popular methods of dimensionality reduction is principal component analysis (PCA).
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] PCA involves changing higher-dimensional data (e.g., 3D) to a smaller space (e.g., 2D).
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] The manifold hypothesis proposes that high-dimensional data sets lie along low-dimensional manifolds, and many dimensionality reduction techniques make this assumption, leading to the areas of manifold learning and manifold regularisation.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Semi-supervised learning falls between unsupervised learning (without any labelled training data) and supervised learning (with completely labelled training data).
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Some of the training examples are missing training labels, yet many machine-learning researchers have found that unlabelled data, when used in conjunction with a small amount of labelled data, can produce a considerable improvement in learning accuracy.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] In weakly supervised learning, the training labels are noisy, limited, or imprecise; however, these labels are often cheaper to obtain, resulting in larger effective training sets.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Reinforcement learning is an area of machine learning concerned with how software agents ought to take actions in an environment to maximise some notion of cumulative reward.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Due to its generality, the field is studied in many other disciplines, such as game theory, control theory, operations research, information theory, simulation-based optimisation, multi-agent systems, swarm intelligence, statistics and genetic algorithms.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] In reinforcement learning, the environment is typically represented as a Markov decision process (MDP).
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Many reinforcement learning algorithms use dynamic programming techniques.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Reinforcement learning algorithms do not assume knowledge of an exact mathematical model of the MDP and are used when exact models are infeasible.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Reinforcement learning algorithms are used in autonomous vehicles or in learning to play a game against a human opponent.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Other approaches have been developed which do not fit neatly into this three-fold categorisation, and sometimes more than one is used by the same machine learning system.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] For example, topic modelling, meta-learning.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Self-learning, as a machine learning paradigm, was introduced in 1982 along with a neural network capable of self-learning, named *crossbar adaptive array* (CAA).
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] It gives a solution to the problem learning without any external reward, by introducing emotion as an internal reward.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Emotion is used as a state evaluation of a self-learning agent.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] The CAA self-learning algorithm computes, in a crossbar fashion, both decisions about actions and emotions (feelings) about consequence situations.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] The system is driven by the interaction between cognition and emotion.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] It is a system with only one input, situation, and only one output, action (or behaviour) a.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] There is neither a separate reinforcement input nor an advice input from the environment.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] The backpropagated value (secondary reinforcement) is the emotion toward the consequence situation.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] The CAA exists in two environments, one is the behavioural environment where it behaves, and the other is the genetic environment, wherefrom it initially and only once receives initial emotions about situations to be encountered in the behavioural environment.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] After receiving the genome (species) vector from the genetic environment, the CAA learns a goal-seeking behaviour in an environment that contains both desirable and undesirable situations.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Several learning algorithms aim at discovering better representations of the inputs provided during training.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Classic examples include principal component analysis and cluster analysis.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Feature learning algorithms, also called representation learning algorithms, often attempt to preserve the information in their input but also transform it in a way that makes it useful, often as a pre-processing step before performing classification or predictions.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] This technique allows reconstruction of the inputs coming from the unknown data-generating distribution, while not being necessarily faithful to configurations that are implausible under that distribution.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] This replaces manual feature engineering, and allows a machine to both learn the features and use them to perform a specific task.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Feature learning can be either supervised or unsupervised.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] In supervised feature learning, features are learned using labelled input data.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Examples include artificial neural networks, multilayer perceptrons, and supervised dictionary learning.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] In unsupervised feature learning, features are learned with unlabelled input data.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Examples include dictionary learning, independent component analysis, autoencoders, matrix factorisation and various forms of clustering.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Manifold learning algorithms attempt to do so under the constraint that the learned representation is low-dimensional.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Sparse coding algorithms attempt to do so under the constraint that the learned representation is sparse, meaning that the mathematical model has many zeros.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Multilinear subspace learning algorithms aim to learn low-dimensional representations directly from tensor representations for multidimensional data, without reshaping them into higher-dimensional vectors.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Deep learning algorithms discover multiple levels of representation, or a hierarchy of features, with higher-level, more abstract features defined in terms of (or generating) lower-level features.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] It has been argued that an intelligent machine learns a representation that disentangles the underlying factors of variation that explain the observed data.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Feature learning is motivated by the fact that machine learning tasks such as classification often require input that is mathematically and computationally convenient to process.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] However, real-world data such as images, video, and sensory data have not yielded attempts to algorithmically define specific features.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] An alternative is to discover such features or representations through examination, without relying on explicit algorithms.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Sparse dictionary learning is a feature learning method where a training example is represented as a linear combination of basis functions and assumed to be a sparse matrix.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] The method is strongly NP-hard and difficult to solve approximately.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] A popular heuristic method for sparse dictionary learning is the *k*-SVD algorithm.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Sparse dictionary learning has been applied in several contexts.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] In classification, the problem is to determine the class to which a previously unseen training example belongs.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] For a dictionary where each class has already been built, a new training example is associated with the class that is best sparsely represented by the corresponding dictionary.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Sparse dictionary learning has also been applied in image denoising.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] The key idea is that a clean image patch can be sparsely represented by an image dictionary, but the noise cannot.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] In data mining, anomaly detection, also known as outlier detection, is the identification of rare items, events or observations that raise suspicions by differing significantly from the majority of the data.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Typically, the anomalous items represent an issue such as bank fraud, a structural defect, medical problems or errors in a text.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Anomalies are referred to as outliers, novelties, noise, deviations and exceptions.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] In particular, in the context of abuse and network intrusion detection, the interesting objects are often not rare, but unexpected bursts of inactivity.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] This pattern does not adhere to the common statistical definition of an outlier as a rare object.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Many outlier detection methods (in particular, unsupervised algorithms) will fail on such data unless aggregated appropriately.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Instead, a cluster analysis algorithm may be able to detect the micro-clusters formed by these patterns.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Three broad categories of anomaly detection techniques exist.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Unsupervised anomaly detection techniques detect anomalies in an unlabelled test data set under the assumption that the majority of the instances in the data set are normal, by looking for instances that seem to fit the least to the remainder of the data set.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Supervised anomaly detection techniques require a data set that has been labelled as "normal" and "abnormal" and involves training a classifier (the key difference from many other statistical classification problems is the inherently unbalanced nature of outlier detection).
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Semi-supervised anomaly detection techniques construct a model representing normal behaviour from a given normal training data set and then test the likelihood of a test instance being generated by the model.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Robot learning is inspired by a multitude of machine learning methods, starting from supervised learning, reinforcement learning, and finally meta-learning (e.g.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Association rule learning is a rule-based machine learning method for discovering relationships between variables in large databases.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] It is intended to identify strong rules discovered in databases using some measure of "interestingness".
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Rule-based machine learning is a general term for any machine learning method that identifies, learns, or evolves "rules" to store, manipulate or apply knowledge.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] The defining characteristic of a rule-based machine learning algorithm is the identification and utilisation of a set of relational rules that collectively represent the knowledge captured by the system.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] This is in contrast to other machine learning algorithms that commonly identify a singular model that can be universally applied to any instance in order to make a prediction.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Rule-based machine learning approaches include learning classifier systems, association rule learning, and artificial immune systems.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Based on the concept of strong rules, Rakesh Agrawal, Tomasz Imieliński and Arun Swami introduced association rules for discovering regularities between products in large-scale transaction data recorded by point-of-sale (POS) systems in supermarkets.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] For example, the rule $\{\mathrm {onions,potatoes} \}\Rightarrow \{\mathrm {burger} \}$ found in the sales data of a supermarket would indicate that if a customer buys onions and potatoes together, they are likely to also buy hamburger meat.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Such information can be used as the basis for decisions about marketing activities such as promotional pricing or product placements.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] In addition to market basket analysis, association rules are employed today in application areas including Web usage mining, intrusion detection, continuous production, and bioinformatics.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] In contrast with sequence mining, association rule learning typically does not consider the order of items either within a transaction or across transactions.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Learning classifier systems (LCS) are a family of rule-based machine learning algorithms that combine a discovery component, typically a genetic algorithm, with a learning component, performing either supervised learning, reinforcement learning, or unsupervised learning.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] They seek to identify a set of context-dependent rules that collectively store and apply knowledge in a piecewise manner to make predictions.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Inductive logic programming (ILP) is an approach to rule learning using logic programming as a uniform representation for input examples, background knowledge, and hypotheses.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Given an encoding of the known background knowledge and a set of examples represented as a logical database of facts, an ILP system will derive a hypothesized logic program that entails all positive and no negative examples.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Inductive programming is a related field that considers any kind of programming language for representing hypotheses (and not only logic programming), such as functional programs.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Inductive logic programming is particularly useful in bioinformatics and natural language processing.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Gordon Plotkin and Ehud Shapiro laid the initial theoretical foundation for inductive machine learning in a logical setting.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Shapiro built their first implementation (Model Inference System) in 1981: a Prolog program that inductively inferred logic programs from positive and negative examples.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] The term *inductive* here refers to philosophical induction, suggesting a theory to explain observed facts, rather than mathematical induction, proving a property for all members of a well-ordered set.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] A **machine learning model** is a type of mathematical model that, once "trained" on a given dataset, can be used to make predictions or classifications on new data.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] During training, a learning algorithm iteratively adjusts the model's internal parameters to minimise errors in its predictions.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] By extension, the term "model" can refer to several levels of specificity, from a general class of models and their associated learning algorithms to a fully trained model with all its internal parameters tuned.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Various types of models have been used and researched for machine learning systems, picking the best model for a task is called model selection.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Artificial neural networks (ANNs), or connectionist systems, are computing systems vaguely inspired by the biological neural networks that constitute animal brains.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Such systems "learn" to perform tasks by considering examples, generally without being programmed with any task-specific rules.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] An ANN is a model based on a collection of connected units or nodes called "artificial neurons", which loosely model the neurons in a biological brain.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Each connection, like the synapses in a biological brain, can transmit information, a "signal", from one artificial neuron to another.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] An artificial neuron that receives a signal can process it and then signal additional artificial neurons connected to it.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] In common ANN implementations, the signal at a connection between artificial neurons is a real number, and the output of each artificial neuron is computed by some non-linear function of the sum of its inputs.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] The connections between artificial neurons are called "edges".
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Artificial neurons and edges typically have a weight that adjusts as learning proceeds.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] The weight increases or decreases the strength of the signal at a connection.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Artificial neurons may have a threshold such that the signal is only sent if the aggregate signal crosses that threshold.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Typically, artificial neurons are aggregated into layers.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Different layers may perform different kinds of transformations on their inputs.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Signals travel from the first layer (the input layer) to the last layer (the output layer), possibly after traversing the layers multiple times.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] The original goal of the ANN approach was to solve problems in the same way that a human brain would.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] However, over time, attention moved to performing specific tasks, leading to deviations from biology.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Artificial neural networks have been used on a variety of tasks, including computer vision, speech recognition, machine translation, social network filtering, playing board and video games and medical diagnosis.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Deep learning consists of multiple hidden layers in an artificial neural network.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] This approach tries to model the way the human brain processes light and sound into vision and hearing.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Some successful applications of deep learning are computer vision and speech recognition.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Decision tree learning uses a decision tree as a predictive model to go from observations about an item (represented in the branches) to conclusions about the item's target value (represented in the leaves).
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] It is one of the predictive modelling approaches used in statistics, data mining, and machine learning.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Tree models where the target variable can take a discrete set of values are called classification trees; in these tree structures, leaves represent class labels, and branches represent conjunctions of features that lead to those class labels.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Decision trees where the target variable can take continuous values (typically real numbers) are called regression trees.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] In decision analysis, a decision tree can be used to visually and explicitly represent decisions and decision making.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] In data mining, a decision tree describes data, but the resulting classification tree can be an input for decision-making.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Random forest regression (RFR) falls under the umbrella of decision tree-based models.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] RFR is an ensemble learning method that builds multiple decision trees and averages their predictions to improve accuracy and to avoid overfitting.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] To build decision trees, RFR uses bootstrapped sampling; for instance, each decision tree is trained on random data from the training set.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] This random selection of RFR for training enables the model to reduce biased predictions and achieve a higher degree of accuracy.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] RFR generates independent decision trees, and it can work on single-output data as well as multiple regressor tasks.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] This makes RFR compatible to be use in various applications.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Support-vector machines (SVMs), also known as support-vector networks, are a set of related supervised learning methods used for classification and regression.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Given a set of training examples, each marked as belonging to one of two categories, an SVM training algorithm builds a model that predicts whether a new example falls into one category.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] An SVM training algorithm is a non-probabilistic, binary, linear classifier, although methods such as Platt scaling exist to use SVM in a probabilistic classification setting.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] In addition to performing linear classification, SVMs can efficiently perform a non-linear classification using what is called the kernel trick, implicitly mapping their inputs into high-dimensional feature spaces.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Regression analysis encompasses a large variety of statistical methods to estimate the relationship between input variables and their associated features.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Its most common form is linear regression, where a single line is drawn to best fit the given data according to a mathematical criterion such as ordinary least squares.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] The latter is often extended by regularisation methods to mitigate overfitting and bias, as in ridge regression.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Multivariate linear regression extends the concept of linear regression to handle multiple dependent variables simultaneously.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] This approach estimates the relationships between a set of input variables and several output variables by fitting a multidimensional linear model.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] It is particularly useful in scenarios where outputs are interdependent or share underlying patterns, such as predicting multiple economic indicators or reconstructing images, which are inherently multi-dimensional.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] A Bayesian network, belief network, or directed acyclic graphical model is a probabilistic graphical model that represents a set of random variables and their conditional independence with a directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] For example, a Bayesian network could represent the probabilistic relationships between diseases and symptoms.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Given symptoms, the network can be used to compute the probabilities of the presence of various diseases.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Efficient algorithms exist that perform inference and learning.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Bayesian networks that model sequences of variables, like speech signals or protein sequences, are called dynamic Bayesian networks.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Generalisations of Bayesian networks that can represent and solve decision problems under uncertainty are called influence diagrams.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] A Gaussian process is a stochastic process in which every finite collection of the random variables in the process has a multivariate normal distribution, and it relies on a pre-defined covariance function, or kernel, that models how pairs of points relate to each other depending on their locations.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Given a set of observed points, or input–output examples, the distribution of the (unobserved) output of a new point as a function of its input data can be directly computed by looking at the observed points and the covariances between those points and the new, unobserved point.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Gaussian processes are popular surrogate models in Bayesian optimisation used to do hyperparameter optimisation.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] A genetic algorithm (GA) is a search algorithm and heuristic technique that mimics the process of natural selection, using methods such as mutation and crossover to generate new genotypes in the hope of finding good solutions to a given problem.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] In machine learning, genetic algorithms were used in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Conversely, machine learning techniques have been used to improve the performance of genetic and evolutionary algorithms.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] The theory of belief functions, also referred to as evidence theory or Dempster–Shafer theory, is a general framework for reasoning with uncertainty, with understood connections to other frameworks such as probability, possibility and imprecise probability theories.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] These theoretical frameworks can be thought of as a kind of learner and have some analogous properties of how evidence is combined (e.g., Dempster's rule of combination), just like how in a pmf-based Bayesian approach would combine probabilities.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] However, there are many caveats to these beliefs functions when compared to Bayesian approaches to incorporate ignorance and uncertainty quantification.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] However, the computational complexity of these algorithms is dependent on the number of propositions (classes), and can lead to a much higher computation time when compared to other machine learning approaches.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Rule-based machine learning (RBML) is a branch of machine learning that automatically discovers and learns 'rules' from data.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] It provides interpretable models, making it useful for decision-making in fields like healthcare, fraud detection, and cybersecurity.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Key RBML techniques includes learning classifier systems, association rule learning, artificial immune systems, and other similar models.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] These methods extract patterns from data and evolve rules over time.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Typically, machine learning models require a high quantity of reliable data to perform accurate predictions.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] When training a machine learning model, machine learning engineers need to target and collect a large and representative sample of data.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Data from the training set can be as varied as a corpus of text, a collection of images, sensor data, and data collected from individual users of a service.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Overfitting is something to watch out for when training a machine learning model.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Trained models derived from biased or non-evaluated data can result in skewed or undesired predictions.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Biased models may result in detrimental outcomes, thereby furthering the negative impacts on society or objectives.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Algorithmic bias is a potential result of data not being fully prepared for training.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Machine learning ethics is becoming a field of study and, notably, becoming integrated within machine learning engineering teams.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Federated learning is an adapted form of distributed artificial intelligence to train machine learning models that decentralises the training process, allowing for users' privacy to be maintained by not needing to send their data to a centralised server.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] This also increases efficiency by decentralising the training process to many devices.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] For example, Gboard uses federated machine learning to train search query prediction models on users' mobile phones without having to send individual searches back to Google.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] In 2006, the media-services provider Netflix held the first "Netflix Prize" competition to find a program to better predict user preferences and improve the accuracy of its existing Cinematch movie recommendation algorithm by at least 10%.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] A joint team made up of researchers from AT&T Labs-Research in collaboration with the teams Big Chaos and Pragmatic Theory built an ensemble model to win the Grand Prize in 2009 for $1 million.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Shortly after the prize was awarded, Netflix realised that viewers' ratings were not the best indicators of their viewing patterns ("everything is a recommendation") and they changed their recommendation engine accordingly.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] In 2010, an article in *The Wall Street Journal* noted the use of machine learning by Rebellion Research to predict the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] In 2012, co-founder of Sun Microsystems, Vinod Khosla, predicted that 80% of medical doctors jobs would be lost in the next two decades to automated machine learning medical diagnostic software.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] In 2014, it was reported that a machine learning algorithm had been applied in the field of art history to study fine art paintings and that it may have revealed previously unrecognised influences among artists.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] In 2019 Springer Nature published the first research book created using machine learning.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] In 2020, machine learning technology was used to help make diagnoses and aid researchers in developing a cure for COVID-19.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Machine learning was recently applied to predict the pro-environmental behaviour of travellers.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Recently, machine learning technology was also applied to optimise smartphone's performance and thermal behaviour based on the user's interaction with the phone.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] When applied correctly, machine learning algorithms (MLAs) can utilise a wide range of company characteristics to predict stock returns without overfitting.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] By employing effective feature engineering and combining forecasts, MLAs can generate results that far surpass those obtained from basic linear techniques like OLS.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Recent advancements in machine learning have extended into the field of quantum chemistry, where novel algorithms now enable the prediction of solvent effects on chemical reactions, thereby offering new tools for chemists to tailor experimental conditions for optimal outcomes.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Machine Learning is becoming a useful tool to investigate and predict evacuation decision-making in large-scale and small-scale disasters.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Different solutions have been tested to predict if and when householders decide to evacuate during wildfires and hurricanes.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p01] Other applications have been focusing on pre evacuation decisions in building fires.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] Although machine learning has been transformative in some fields, machine-learning programs often fail to deliver expected results.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] Reasons for this are numerous: lack of (suitable) data, lack of access to the data, data bias, privacy problems, badly chosen tasks and algorithms, wrong tools and people, lack of resources, and evaluation problems.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] The "black box theory" poses another yet significant challenge.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] Black box refers to a situation where the algorithm producing an output is entirely opaque, meaning that even the designers of an application cannot audit the pattern that the machine extracted from the data.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] The House of Lords Select Committee, which claimed that such an "intelligence system" that could have a "substantial impact on an individual's life" would not be considered acceptable unless it provided "a full and satisfactory explanation for the decisions" it makes.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] In 2018, a self-driving car from Uber failed to detect a pedestrian, who was killed after a collision.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] Attempts to use machine learning in healthcare with the IBM Watson system failed to deliver even after years of time and billions of dollars invested.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] Microsoft's Bing Chat chatbot has been reported to produce hostile and offensive response against its users.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] Machine learning has been used as a strategy to update the evidence related to a systematic review and increased reviewer burden related to the growth of biomedical literature.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] While it has improved with training sets, it has not yet developed sufficiently to reduce the workload burden without limiting the necessary sensitivity for the findings research itself.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] Explainable AI (XAI), or Interpretable AI, or Explainable Machine Learning (XML), is artificial intelligence (AI) in which humans can understand the decisions or predictions made by the AI.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] It contrasts with the "black box" concept in machine learning where even its designers cannot explain why an AI arrived at a specific decision.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] By refining the mental models of users of AI-powered systems and dismantling their misconceptions, XAI promises to help users perform more effectively.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] XAI may be an implementation of the social right to explanation.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] Settling on a bad, overly complex theory gerrymandered to fit all the past training data is known as overfitting.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] Many systems attempt to reduce overfitting by rewarding a theory in accordance with how well it fits the data but penalising the theory in accordance with how complex the theory is.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] It is unclear to what extent the phenomenon threatens the long-term development of such models, and some techniques have been proposed to mitigate the effect.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] , inconsistent carriage lengths, unnatural amounts of visual noise, and a carriage bending along its length as it rounds the turn.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] In the field of artificial intelligence (AI), a hallucination or artificial hallucination (also called bullshitting, confabulation, or delusion) is a response generated by AI that contains false or misleading information presented as fact.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] The term draws a loose analogy with human psychology, where a hallucination typically involves false *percepts*.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] For example, a chatbot powered by large language models (LLMs), like ChatGPT, may embed plausible-sounding random falsehoods within its generated content.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] Detecting and mitigating errors and hallucinations pose significant challenges for practical deployment and reliability of LLMs in high-stakes scenarios, such as chip design, supply chain logistics, and medical diagnostics.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] Some software engineers and statisticians have criticized the specific term "AI hallucination" for unreasonably anthropomorphizing computers.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] Symbolic artificial intelligence models generally do not produce hallucinations, unlike large language models.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] Learners can also be disappointed by "learning the wrong lesson".
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] A toy example is that an image classifier trained only on pictures of brown horses and black cats might conclude that all brown patches are likely to be horses.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] Modifying these patterns on a legitimate image can result in "adversarial" images that the system misclassifies.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] Adversarial vulnerabilities can also result in nonlinear systems or from non-pattern perturbations.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] For some systems, it is possible to change the output by only changing a single adversarially chosen pixel.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] Machine learning models are often vulnerable to manipulation or evasion via adversarial machine learning.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] Researchers have demonstrated how backdoors can be placed undetectably into classifying (e.g., for categories "spam" and "not spam" of posts) machine learning models that are often developed or trained by third parties.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] Parties can change the classification of any input, including in cases for which a type of data/software transparency is provided, possibly including white-box access.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] Classification of machine learning models can be validated by accuracy estimation techniques like the holdout method, which splits the data into a training and test set (conventionally 2/3 training set and 1/3 test set designation) and evaluates the performance of the training model on the test set.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] In comparison, the K-fold-cross-validation method randomly partitions the data into K subsets and then K experiments are performed each considering 1 subset for evaluation and the remaining K-1 subsets for training the model.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] In addition to the holdout and cross-validation methods, bootstrap, which samples n instances with replacement from the dataset, can be used to assess model accuracy.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] In addition to overall accuracy, investigators frequently report sensitivity and specificity, meaning true positive rate (TPR) and true negative rate (TNR), respectively.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] Similarly, investigators sometimes report the false positive rate (FPR) as well as the false negative rate (FNR).
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] However, these rates are ratios that fail to reveal their numerators and denominators.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] Receiver operating characteristic (ROC), along with the accompanying Area Under the ROC Curve (AUC), offer additional tools for classification model assessment.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] Higher AUC is associated with a better performing model.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] The ethics of artificial intelligence covers a broad range of topics within AI that are considered to have particular ethical stakes.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] This includes algorithmic biases, fairness, accountability, transparency, privacy, and regulation, particularly where systems influence or automate human decision-making.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] Some application areas may also have particularly important ethical implications, like healthcare, education, criminal justice, or the military.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] Different machine learning approaches can suffer from different data biases.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] A machine learning system trained specifically on current customers may not be able to predict the needs of new customer groups that are not represented in the training data.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] When trained on human-made data, machine learning is likely to pick up the constitutional and unconscious biases already present in society.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] Systems that are trained on datasets collected with biases may exhibit these biases upon use (algorithmic bias), thus digitising cultural prejudices.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] For example, in 1988, the UK's Commission for Racial Equality found that St.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] George's Medical School had been using a computer program trained from data of previous admissions staff and this program had denied nearly 60 candidates who were found to either be women or have non-European-sounding names.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] Using job hiring data from a firm with racist hiring policies may lead to a machine learning system duplicating the bias by scoring job applicants by similarity to previous successful applicants.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] Another example includes predictive policing company Geolitica's predictive algorithm that resulted in "disproportionately high levels of over-policing in low-income and minority communities" after being trained with historical crime data.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] In fact, according to research carried out by the Computing Research Association in 2021, "female faculty make up just 16.1%" of all faculty members who focus on AI among several universities around the world.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] Furthermore, among the group of "new U.S. resident AI PhD graduates," 45% identified as white, 22.4% as Asian, 3.2% as Hispanic, and 2.4% as African American, which further demonstrates a lack of diversity in the field of AI.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] Language models learned from data have been shown to contain human-like biases.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] Because human languages contain biases, machines trained on language *corpora* will necessarily also learn these biases.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] In 2016, Microsoft tested Tay, a chatbot that learned from Twitter, and it quickly picked up racist and sexist language.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] In an experiment carried out by ProPublica, an investigative journalism organisation, a machine learning algorithm's insight into the recidivism rates among prisoners falsely flagged "black defendants high risk twice as often as white defendants".
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] In 2015, Google Photos once tagged a couple of black people as gorillas, which caused controversy.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] The gorilla label was subsequently removed, and in 2023, it still cannot recognise gorillas.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] Similar issues with recognising non-white people have been found in many other systems.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] Because of such challenges, the effective use of machine learning may take longer to be adopted in other domains.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] Concern for fairness in machine learning, that is, reducing bias in machine learning and propelling its use for human good, is increasingly expressed by artificial intelligence scientists, including Fei-Fei Li, who said that "[t]here's nothing artificial about AI.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] It's inspired by people, it's created by people, and—most importantly—it impacts people.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] There are concerns among health care professionals that these systems might not be designed in the public's interest but as income-generating machines.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] This is especially true in the United States, where there is a long-standing ethical dilemma of improving health care, but also increasing profits.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] For example, the algorithms could be designed to provide patients with unnecessary tests or medication in which the algorithm's proprietary owners hold stakes.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] There is potential for machine learning in health care to provide professionals with an additional tool to diagnose, medicate, and plan recovery paths for patients, but this requires these biases to be mitigated.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] Since the 2010s, advances in both machine learning algorithms and computer hardware have led to more efficient methods for training deep neural networks (a particular narrow subdomain of machine learning) that contain many layers of nonlinear hidden units.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] By 2019, graphics processing units (GPUs), often with AI-specific enhancements, had displaced CPUs as the dominant method of training large-scale commercial cloud AI.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] OpenAI estimated the hardware compute used in the largest deep learning projects from AlexNet (2012) to AlphaZero (2017), and found a 300,000-fold increase in the amount of compute required, with a doubling-time trendline of 3.4 months.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] Tensor Processing Units (TPUs) are specialised hardware accelerators developed by Google specifically for machine learning workloads.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] Unlike general-purpose GPUs and FPGAs, TPUs are optimised for tensor computations, making them particularly efficient for deep learning tasks such as training and inference.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] They are widely used in Google Cloud AI services and large-scale machine learning models like Google's DeepMind AlphaFold and large language models.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] TPUs leverage matrix multiplication units and high-bandwidth memory to accelerate computations while maintaining energy efficiency.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] Since their introduction in 2016, TPUs have become a key component of AI infrastructure, especially in cloud-based environments.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] Neuromorphic computing refers to a class of computing systems designed to emulate the structure and functionality of biological neural networks.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] These systems may be implemented through software-based simulations on conventional hardware or through specialised hardware architectures.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] A physical neural network is a specific type of neuromorphic hardware that relies on electrically adjustable materials, such as memristors, to emulate the function of neural synapses.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] The term "physical neural network" highlights the use of physical hardware for computation, as opposed to software-based implementations.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] It broadly refers to artificial neural networks that use materials with adjustable resistance to replicate neural synapses.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] Embedded machine learning is a sub-field of machine learning where models are deployed on embedded systems with limited computing resources, such as wearable computers, edge devices and microcontrollers.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] Running models directly on these devices eliminates the need to transfer and store data on cloud servers for further processing, thereby reducing the risk of data breaches, privacy leaks and theft of intellectual property, personal data and business secrets.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] Embedded machine learning can be achieved through various techniques, such as hardware acceleration, approximate computing, and model optimization.
[src:weights-and-biases/machine-learning-p02] Common optimization techniques include pruning, quantisation, knowledge distillation, low-rank factorisation, network architecture search, and parameter sharing.
[src:weights-and-biases/mlops] The word is a compound of "machine learning" and the continuous delivery practice (CI/CD) of DevOps in the software field.
[src:weights-and-biases/mlops] Machine learning models are tested and developed in isolated experimental systems.
[src:weights-and-biases/mlops] When an algorithm is ready to be launched, MLOps is practiced between data scientists, DevOps, and machine learning engineers to transition the algorithm to production systems.
[src:weights-and-biases/mlops] Similar to DevOps or DataOps approaches, MLOps seeks to increase automation and improve the quality of production models, while also focusing on business and regulatory requirements.
[src:weights-and-biases/mlops] While MLOps started as a set of best practices, it is slowly evolving into an independent approach to ML lifecycle management.
[src:weights-and-biases/mlops] MLOps applies to the entire lifecycle - from integrating with model generation (software development lifecycle, continuous integration/continuous delivery), orchestration, and deployment, to health, diagnostics, governance, and business metrics.
[src:weights-and-biases/mlops] MLOps is a paradigm, including aspects like best practices, sets of concepts, as well as a development culture when it comes to the end-to-end conceptualization, implementation, monitoring, deployment, and scalability of machine learning products.
[src:weights-and-biases/mlops] Most of all, it is an engineering practice that leverages three contributing disciplines: machine learning, software engineering (especially DevOps), and data engineering.
[src:weights-and-biases/mlops] MLOps is aimed at productionizing machine learning systems by bridging the gap between development (Dev) and operations (Ops).
[src:weights-and-biases/mlops] Interest in operationalizing machine learning systems began to grow in the mid-2010s as ML projects started moving from experimentation to production use.
[src:weights-and-biases/mlops] The challenges associated with sustaining such systems were highlighted in a 2015 paper.
[src:weights-and-biases/mlops] The predicted growth in machine learning included an estimated doubling of ML pilots and implementations from 2017 to 2018, and again from 2018 to 2020.
[src:weights-and-biases/mlops] Reports show a majority (up to 88%) of corporate machine learning initiatives are struggling to move beyond test stages.
[src:weights-and-biases/mlops] However, those organizations that actually put machine learning into production saw a 3–15% profit margin increases.
[src:weights-and-biases/mlops] The MLOps market size was USD 2,191.8 Million in 2024, and is projected to be USD 16,613.4 Million in 2030.
[src:weights-and-biases/mlops] Machine Learning systems can be categorized in eight different categories: data collection, data processing, feature engineering, data labeling, model design, model training and optimization, endpoint deployment, and endpoint monitoring.
[src:weights-and-biases/mlops] Each step in the machine learning lifecycle is built in its own system, but requires interconnection.
[src:weights-and-biases/mlops] These are the minimum systems that enterprises need to scale machine learning within their organization.
[src:weights-and-biases/mlops] A standard practice, such as MLOps, takes into account each of the aforementioned areas, which can help enterprises optimize workflows and avoid issues during implementation.
[src:weights-and-biases/mlops] Vendors such as Adaptive ML deliver commercial reinforcement learning operations (RLOps) and MLOps-infrastructure, targeting organizations deploying large language models in production.
[src:weights-and-biases/mlops] A common architecture of an MLOps system would include data science platforms where models are constructed and the analytical engines where computations are performed, with the MLOps tool orchestrating the movement of machine learning models, data and outcomes between the systems.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] The first to stress the importance of reproducibility in science was the Anglo-Irish chemist Robert Boyle, in England in the 17th century.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] Boyle's air pump was designed to generate and study vacuum, which at the time was a very controversial concept.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] Indeed, distinguished philosophers such as René Descartes and Thomas Hobbes denied the very possibility of vacuum existence.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] Historians of science Steven Shapin and Simon Schaffer, in their 1985 book *Leviathan and the Air-Pump*, describe the debate between Boyle and Hobbes, ostensibly over the nature of vacuum, as fundamentally an argument about how useful knowledge should be gained.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] Boyle, a pioneer of the experimental method, maintained that the foundations of knowledge should be constituted by experimentally produced facts, which can be made believable to a scientific community by their reproducibility.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] By repeating the same experiment over and over again, Boyle argued, the certainty of fact will emerge.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] The air pump, which in the 17th century was a complicated and expensive apparatus to build, also led to one of the first documented disputes over the reproducibility of a particular scientific phenomenon.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] In the 1660s, the Dutch scientist Christiaan Huygens built his own air pump in Amsterdam, the first one outside the direct management of Boyle and his assistant at the time Robert Hooke.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] Huygens reported an effect he termed "anomalous suspension", in which water appeared to levitate in a glass jar inside his air pump (in fact suspended over an air bubble), but Boyle and Hooke could not replicate this phenomenon in their own pumps.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] As Shapin and Schaffer describe, "it became clear that unless the phenomenon could be produced in England with one of the two pumps available, then no one in England would accept the claims Huygens had made, or his competence in working the pump".
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] Huygens was finally invited to England in 1663, and under his personal guidance Hooke was able to replicate anomalous suspension of water.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] Following this Huygens was elected a Foreign Member of the Royal Society.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] However, Shapin and Schaffer also note that "the accomplishment of replication was dependent on contingent acts of judgment.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] One cannot write down a formula saying when replication was or was not achieved".
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] The philosopher of science Karl Popper noted briefly in his famous 1934 book *The Logic of Scientific Discovery* that "non-reproducible single occurrences are of no significance to science".
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] Such assertions express a common dogma in modern science that reproducibility is a necessary condition (although not necessarily sufficient) for establishing a scientific fact, and in practice for establishing scientific authority in any field of knowledge.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] However, as noted above by Shapin and Schaffer, this dogma is not well-formulated quantitatively, such as statistical significance for instance, and therefore it is not explicitly established how many times must a fact be replicated to be considered reproducible.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] Two major steps are naturally distinguished in connection with reproducibility of experimental or observational studies: when new data are obtained in the attempt to achieve it, the term *replicability* is often used, and the new study is a *replication* or *replicate* of the original one.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] Obtaining the same results when analyzing the data set of the original study again with the same procedures, many authors use the term *reproducibility* in a narrow, technical sense coming from its use in computational research.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] *Repeatability* is related to the *repetition* of the experiment within the same study by the same researchers.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] Reproducibility in the original, wide sense is only acknowledged if a replication performed by an *independent researcher team* is successful.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] The terms reproducibility and replicability sometimes appear even in the scientific literature with reversed meaning, as different research fields settled on their own definitions for the same terms.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] In chemistry, the terms reproducibility and repeatability are used with a specific quantitative meaning.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] In inter-laboratory experiments, a concentration or other quantity of a chemical substance is measured repeatedly in different laboratories to assess the variability of the measurements.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] Then, the standard deviation of the difference between two values obtained within the same laboratory is called repeatability.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] The standard deviation for the difference between two measurement from different laboratories is called *reproducibility*.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] These measures are related to the more general concept of variance components in metrology.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] The term *reproducible research* refers to the idea that scientific results should be documented in such a way that their deduction is fully transparent.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] This requires a detailed description of the methods used to obtain the data and making the full dataset and the code to calculate the results easily accessible.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] This is the essential part of open science.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] To make any research project computationally reproducible, general practice involves all data and files being clearly separated, labelled, and documented.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] All operations should be fully documented and automated as much as practicable, avoiding manual intervention where feasible.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] The workflow should be designed as a sequence of smaller steps that are combined so that the intermediate outputs from one step directly feed as inputs into the next step.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] Version control should be used as it lets the history of the project be easily reviewed and allows for the documenting and tracking of changes in a transparent manner.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] A basic workflow for reproducible research involves data acquisition, data processing and data analysis.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] Data acquisition primarily consists of obtaining primary data from a primary source such as surveys, field observations, experimental research, or obtaining data from an existing source.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] Data processing involves the processing and review of the raw data collected in the first stage, and includes data entry, data manipulation and filtering and may be done using software.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] The data should be digitized and prepared for data analysis.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] Data may be analysed with the use of software to interpret or visualise statistics or data to produce the desired results of the research such as quantitative results including figures and tables.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] The use of software and automation enhances the reproducibility of research methods.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] There are systems that facilitate such documentation, like the R Markdown language or the Jupyter notebook.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] The Open Science Framework provides a platform and useful tools to support reproducible research.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] Psychology has seen a renewal of internal concerns about irreproducible results (see the entry on replicability crisis for empirical results on success rates of replications).
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] Researchers showed in a 2006 study that, of 141 authors of a publication from the American Psychological Association (APA) empirical articles, 103 (73%) did not respond with their data over a six-month period.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] In a follow-up study published in 2015, it was found that 246 out of 394 contacted authors of papers in APA journals did not share their data upon request (62%).
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] In a 2012 paper, it was suggested that researchers should publish data along with their works, and a dataset was released alongside as a demonstration.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] In 2017, an article published in *Scientific Data* suggested that this may not be sufficient and that the whole analysis context should be disclosed.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] In economics, concerns have been raised in relation to the credibility and reliability of published research.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] In other sciences, reproducibility is regarded as fundamental and is often a prerequisite to research being published, however in economic sciences it is not seen as a priority of the greatest importance.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] Most peer-reviewed economic journals do not take any substantive measures to ensure that published results are reproducible, however, the top economics journals have been moving to adopt mandatory data and code archives.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] There is low or no incentives for researchers to share their data, and authors would have to bear the costs of compiling data into reusable forms.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] Economic research is often not reproducible as only a portion of journals have adequate disclosure policies for datasets and program code, and even if they do, authors frequently do not comply with them or they are not enforced by the publisher.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] A Study of 599 articles published in 37 peer-reviewed journals revealed that while some journals have achieved significant compliance rates, significant portion have only partially complied, or not complied at all.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] On an article level, the average compliance rate was 47.5%; and on a journal level, the average compliance rate was 38%, ranging from 13% to 99%.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] A 2018 study published in the journal *PLOS ONE* found that 14.4% of a sample of public health statistics researchers had shared their data or code or both.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] There have been initiatives to improve reporting and hence reproducibility in the medical literature for many years, beginning with the CONSORT initiative, which is now part of a wider initiative, the EQUATOR Network.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] This group has recently turned its attention to how better reporting might reduce waste in research, especially biomedical research.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] Reproducible research is key to new discoveries in pharmacology.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] A Phase I discovery will be followed by Phase II reproductions as a drug develops towards commercial production.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] In recent decades Phase II success has fallen from 28% to 18%.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] A 2011 study found that 65% of medical studies were inconsistent when re-tested, and only 6% were completely reproducible.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] Some efforts have been made to increase replicability beyond the social and biomedical sciences.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] Studies in the humanities tend to rely more on expertise and hermeneutics which may make replicability more difficult.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] Nonetheless, some efforts have been made to call for more transparency and documentation in the humanities.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] Hideyo Noguchi became famous for correctly identifying the bacterial agent of syphilis, but also claimed that he could culture this agent in his laboratory.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] Nobody else has been able to produce this latter result.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] In March 1989, University of Utah chemists Stanley Pons and Martin Fleischmann reported the production of excess heat that could only be explained by a nuclear process ("cold fusion").
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] The report was astounding given the simplicity of the equipment: it was essentially an electrolysis cell containing heavy water and a palladium cathode which rapidly absorbed the deuterium produced during electrolysis.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] The news media reported on the experiments widely, and it was a front-page item on many newspapers around the world (see science by press conference).
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] Over the next several months others tried to replicate the experiment, but were unsuccessful.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] Nikola Tesla claimed as early as 1899 to have used a high frequency current to light gas-filled lamps from over 25 miles (40 km) away without using wires.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] In 1904 he built Wardenclyffe Tower on Long Island to demonstrate means to send and receive power without connecting wires.
[src:weights-and-biases/reproducibility] The facility was never fully operational and was not completed due to economic problems, so no attempt to reproduce his first result was ever carried out.
